│ with vector extensions).\n\n### 1. Understanding the         │
│ Issue\n\nThe core of the problem lies in the differing trip  │
│ count estimations by the two cost models. The loop's trip    │
│ count is variable, depending on the initial value of the     │
│ induction variable `%iv`, which is determined by a `select`  │
│ instruction. The trip count can be either 1 or 3.\n\n- The   │
│ **legacy cost model** conservatively estimates the trip      │
│ count. Due to the variability and the way Scalar Evolution   │
│ (SE) analyzes the loop, it concludes that vectorization is   │
│ not beneficial because the maximum trip count it can prove   │
│ (`getSmallestMaxTripCount`) is 1. A trip count of 1 means no │
│ vectorization is possible.\n\n- The **VPlan-based cost       │
│ model**, on the other hand, uses a more optimistic approach. │
│ It calculates costs based on the assumption that the loop    │
│ will execute enough times to make vectorization worthwhile   │
│ (using `VF.getKnownMinValue()`, which is 2 for a scalable    │
│ vector). This leads it to select a vectorization factor (VF) │
│ of `scalable<2> x i64`.\n\nThis divergence in chosen         │
│ vectorization factors (scalar vs. `scalable<2>`) triggers    │
│ the assertion `BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width`, as the   │
│ condition for allowing a mismatch                            │
│ (`planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`) is not met.\n\n### │
